@node Introduction
 This program allows one to alter the settings in the settings file for
 Oxxi Presentation Master.  The settings file is kept on the s: directory
 and is named ".PM.settings".  This file is created from scratch upon
 installation of Presentation Master and should only be revised via this
 program, unless you know exactly what you are doing.  It is in ASCII so
 one may examine the file if need be.
@endnode

@node DefaultPaths "Default Disk Paths"
 These entries allow you to alter the default directory where various
 types of information is to be found by Presentation Master:

  SHOW Path: This is where Presentation Master will first look when
    opening/saving a show file.
  IFF Path: This is where Presentation Master will first look when
    opening/saving an IFF picture.
  PolyFont Path: This is the initial path for opening of Polygon Font
    files in the PolyFont module.
  Template Path: This is the initial path for opening of templates.
  Bullet Fonts: This is the initial path for opening of Compugraphic
    Intellifonts (Bullet fonts) from within the BulletFont module.
  Clip Art: This is the initial base path for opening of clip art eps
    image files.
  Backgrounds: This is the initial path for opening of IFF background
    images for use as backdrops for slides.
  Module Path: This is the path where Presentation Master will search
    for modules upon being initially run.  Any modules found here will
    be assembled into lists according to the type of module and will
    be used to build certain menus in Presentation Master for the
    selection of a module for some operation.  This path will also be
    used by various other misc. files such as the process color files.

 N.B. that most of these are simply the initial path used by the file
 requester when an open/save operation is requested.  Once a file is
 opened, its name internally contains the complete path and it will be
 properly loaded from the path it resides in.  Changing these entries
 will NOT change paths on existing file entries in shows.
@endnode

@node TemplateLoad "Preload Template"
 If an entry is placed here, then this will be assumed to be a path/file
 for a template to be preloaded upon running Presentation Master.
 Normally this is left empty since the template is specified on the
 project file which is saved by doing a save settings out of the main
 menu from within Presentation Master.
@endnode

@node OpModes "Operational Modes"
 This permits the selection of certain operational modes within
 Presentation Master:

  Initial Mode: Here you can choose between "Single Slide" and "Slide
    Sorter".  This determines the initial screen opened upon running
    Presentation Master.  If "Single Slide" is selected (the default)
    then the first screen you will see will be a slide using the first
    template of the template family specified on the project file.  If
    no template was specified, then it will be using a very simple
    built-in template.  If "Slide Sorter" is selected then the first
    screen will be the slide sorter with an empty slide in the parent
    position.  N.B. that Presentation Master was intended to be always
    started from the Slide Sorter screen, since it is the nerve center
    to the entire program.  However, the Single Slide starting mode was
    put in at the request of some testers who thought that the slide
    sorter was too complex for a first time user to be confronted with.
    It is recommended that once you become familiar with the program,
    you switch the initial mode to "Slide Sorter" as soon as possible.

  Hires Flicker: Here you can turn "Reduce Flicker" on/off.  When it is
    on, all button rendering will be double lines to reduce flicker on
    a standard Amiga video display.  Also, most of the time, the dither
    patterns will also be doubled which makes a more coarse dither
    pattern, but will reduce flicker when the two colors being dithered
    have a high contrast.  This should be turned off if you have a
    non-flickering monitor such as a high-persistence monitor or a
    MultiSync monitor with a flicker fixer (or on an A3000) since you get
    the best quality display in that mode.  N.B. that vulcanized shows
    will use this setting to determine the type of dithering to use
    when rendering slides.  You may think about who you are going to
    distribute the vulcanized show to and make sure you turn this on if
    they will have displays subject to flicker (or if you are intending
    to video tape the show).

  Memory Options:  Here you have a choice of memory saving methods.  This
    ONLY applies if you are running the overlay version of Presentation
    Master.  Otherwise it is ignored!  The options are Normal, Reduce, and
    Minimum Ram.  "Normal Ram" makes the overlay program have all the same
    operation as the non-overlay version, except for the time delays for
    loading overlays.  "Reduce Ram" will eliminate many internal buffers
    which will slow things down since objects will have to be redrawn more
    frequently, but it will save a bit more ram.  "Minimum Ram" eliminates
    a few more buffers.  This mode is very bothersome since there is a
    lot more redraws required, and also the entire background will often
    dissappear in some places such as in the bar chart module.  However,
    this last mode is required if you really are short on ram (such as
    on a 2Mb A3000 with kickstart loaded into ram).  See the help file
    for Presentation Master for more information on memory considerations.
@endnode

@node Save "Save Defaults or Cancel"
 The "Save Defaults" button will save the current settings back out to the
 "s:.PM.settings" file and will then exit.  The "Cancel" button will
 terminate without changing this file at all.
@endnode

@node FontEquiv "PostScript Font Equivalencing"
 This section of the screen allows the alteration of the equivalencing
 between screen fonts (Amiga fonts) and those used on a PostScript
 output device.  Each entry consists of a font family name which will
 appear in yellow on the font selector popup within Presentation Master.
 Then there is an Amiga font for on-screen rendering.  Note that for
 on-screen rendering, italic and boldface (or both) are done
 algorithmically (in other words, the same font is used but it is altered
 to give the italic and/or boldface appearance).  In PostScript there
 are separate fonts for each since they are really different in design.
 The biggest difference usually is in the normal/italic comparison.
 Normally if a PostScript font is designated "Italic" then it has been
 redesigned with different characters for italic (compare the 'a').
 If it is designated "Oblique" then it is normally just skewed for the
 italic representation, as are the on-screen fonts on the Amiga.

 At present, Presentation Master cannot download fonts, so you are
 limited to those present on the device.  For most low-end PostScript
 laser printers, these are a set of standard 35 fonts and the default
 font equivalencing provided on installation of Presentation Master
 has entries to access these 35 fonts.  Some printers may have minor
 variations in the names of some fonts.  The main example is the QMS
 ColorScript series of printers which have "Helvitica-Condensed" instead
 of the more standard "Helvetica-Narrow".  You should run a test pattern
 from the PostScript module on your printer which will print a list of
 all the fonts available.  Then you can come here and revise the list
 if necessary.

 There are some commercial font downloaders which can be used to
 place additional fonts on your printer which will stay around until
 the printer is reset.  If you use one of these, then you can add the
 additional fonts to this list.

 When rendering to the screen, the indicated font will be used at
 whatever font size you select.  When sending the text to the PostScript
 device, the size and length of the on-screen text will be sent to
 the PostScript device and the indicated PostScript font will be scaled
 to provide the same dimensions.  Thus, if you use an on-screen font
 with substantially different aspect ratio from the PostScript font,
 the PostScript font will be scaled to the same aspect ratio.  This can
 be used to advantage at times to get, for instance, a condensed or
 stretched version of a standard font.

 There are buttons for inserting a new font entry, cloning an existing
 entry, or deleting an entry.
@endnode

@node AreaBuffer
 The AreaBuffer is a buffer used for holding intermediate data on
 doing area fills within the Amiga.  The default value of 5000 bytes
 will be used if you leave this entry ==0.  However, if you are
 doing some complex shapes and some area fills just dissappear and
 never are rendered, then perhaps this has to be increased.  A value
 of 15000 seems to handle anything tried at Oxxi to date.  However,
 this should only be increased if you have ample memory.
@endnode
